<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="73" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName LSID="http://species-id.net/wiki/Peltonotus_favonius" authority="Jameson &amp; Wada, 2009" authorityName="Jameson &amp; Wada" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Peltonotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peltonotus favonius" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favonius">Peltonotus favonius Jameson &amp; Wada, 2009</taxonomicName>
Figs 4, 39, 51, 60, 75
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="73" type="diagnosis (male and female)">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="73">Diagnosis (male and female).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="73">Length ~14.6 mm, color overall black, elytra black or dark reddish brown with iridescent bloom (Fig. 4), head with simple punctures (lacking setae), labrum bi-emarginate, mentum rounded in apical half, labial palpomere 2 not enlarged or obviously dorsoventrally flattened, mala lacking lamellate setal brush (Fig. 39), maxillary stipes without setae curled at apices (Fig. 39), male protibia bidentate (Fig. 51), form of parameres (Fig. 60), female epipleuron broadly expanded, weakly convex, extending from base to metacoxa, lacking incised apex (Fig. 75).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="73">Vietnam and Myanmar.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="73">
This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Peltonotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peltonotus pruinosus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">Peltonotus pruinosus</taxonomicName>
, a species for which only the female holotype is known. Previously, this species was only known from the male holotype specimen from Vietnam.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
